{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-04-20T18:39:06.641911+00:00", "modified": "2026-04-22T15:58:42.207163+00:00", "id": 19668954, "conceptrecid": "19668953", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19668954", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.19668953", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19668954", "metadata": {"title": "Flower discrimination by pollinators in a dynamic chemical environment", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19668954", "publication_date": "2014", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) How hawkmoths sniff out a flower\n            \n              Pollinators such as butterflies and bees are the true targets of the flower odors we love so much. Though we might imagine insects \"following their noses,\" the wealth of odors in the real world can drown out the smell of a flower, making it hard to find. Riffel\n              et al.\n              found that hawkmoths find angel's trumpets by creating a neuronal picture within their antennal lobe, the part of the moth brain that receives olfactory signals from the antennae (see the Perspective by Szyszka). The picture represents both the flower and the background odors. Finding a flower involves a complex reading of both background and target odors, and changes in the background odors\u2014including human pollutants\u2014can hinder the process.\n            \n            \n              Science\n              , this issue p.\n              1515\n              ; see also p.\n              1454\n            \n          , \n            \n              Moths find flowers by building an odor map in their antennal lobes.\n              \n                [Also see Perspective by\n                Szyszka\n                ]\n              \n            \n          , \n            \n              Pollinators use their sense of smell to locate flowers from long distances, but little is known about how they are able to discriminate their target odor from a m\u00e9lange of other natural and anthropogenic odors. Here, we measured the plume from\n              Datura wrightii\n              flowers, a nectar resource for\n              Manduca sexta\n              moths, and show that the scent was dynamic and rapidly embedded among background odors. The moth's ability to track the odor was dependent on the background and odor frequency. By influencing the balance of excitation and inhibition in the antennal lobe, background odors altered the neuronal representation of the target odor and the ability of the moth to track the plume. These results show that the mix of odors present in the environment influences the pollinator's olfactory ability.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Riffell, Jeffrey A.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Shlizerman, Eli", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Sanders, Elischa", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Abrell, Leif", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Medina, Billie", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Hinterwirth, Armin J.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Kutz, J. Nathan", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/f192d22f3a75cc0eed4f24b5904b30a2", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/f55b33fbaf4ffbc6dc4f80424ce6fb512215f8a53fbe60bac95780eca7edd026", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/FU8KR4FX", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/FU8KR4FX", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/02a64b9d2cc3229ebf85df68766b333c!/b243957-246389", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/0157e8ec3f1f8eb877e7b6cd6fde26bc", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "do